{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2goncharova_ver03/data/sn83045462/00280605189/1948121001/0554.xml":{"full_text":"Wadleigh, Spy Case Witness,\nCalled a'Thinking Machine'\nHenry Julian Wadleigh was de\nscribed by a former associate in the\nState Department today as a \u201cthink\ning machine\u201d who might well have\nbeen nicknamed \u201cthe Brain.\u201d\nThis official said he never saw\nMr. Wadleigh give any appearance\nof being concerned with commu\nnism as such or the political impli\ncations of it.\nHe was surprised at Mr. Wad\nleigh\u2019s involvement in the House\nCommittee on Un-American Activi\nties investigation of Communist es\npionage.\nMr. Wadleigh worked as an econ\nomist in the State Department from\n1936 to 1943. He was concerned\nwith work on reciprocal trade\nagreements and during the latter\npart of his State employment, with\nplanning for the economic reha\nbilitation of Italy.\nNot a Policymaker.\nA department official recalled to\nday that Mr. Wadleigh never held a\nvery responsible position so far as\npolicymaking was concerned.\n\u201cHe was definitely a thinljing ma\nchine and was used as such,\u201d this\nofficial said. \u201cHe was not a doer or\nan administrator, but was good at\nfiguring out the intricacies of higher\neconomics.\n\u201cIf I had picked a nickname for\nhim, I would have called him \u201cthe\nBrain.\u2019\n\u201cHe appeared to be a very pre\ncise, coldly intellectual type of fel\nlow. But he gave no impression of\nbeing a radical intellectual, and I\nnever got the impression that he\nwas politically radical.\nPleasant and Affable.\n\"Although not a hail-fellow-well\nmet good mixer, he was pleasant and\naffable and got along all right with\nhis associates.\u201d\nThe State Department register,\nissued October 1, 1942, gives the fol\nlowing information on Mr. Wad\nleigh:\nBom at Greenfield, Mass., Febru\nary 4, 1904. He took master of arts\ndegree at Oxford in 1926, did grad\nuate work at the London School of\nEconomics 1926-1928; the University\nof Kiel, Germany, 1928-9, and the\nUniversity of Chicago 1929-30.\nHe became an economist with the\nFederal Farm Board in 1930, went\nto the Agriculture Department in\n1932 and to the Agricultural Adjust\nment Administration in 1935, re\nmaining there into 1936.\nOn March 2, 1936, he was ap\npointed an economic analyst in the\nState Department with a salary of\n$4,600. He became a divisional as\nsistant on July 1, 1939, and on Feb\nruary 3, 1941, received a salary in\ncrease to $5,600. On June 1, 1942,\nhe became assistant chief of the\ndivision of special research at a\nsalary of $6,500.\nThen he was sent to Italy for\nwork with the Allied Control Com\nmission and worked later for UNRRA\nand more recently with the Italian\ngovernment. He told the committee\nI yesterday he now is unemployed.\nRobert Quillen Dies;\nSharp Column Made\nTramp Printer Famous\nBy the Associated Press\nFOUNTAIN INN, S. C., Dec. 10.\u2014\nRobert Quillen, 61, the sage of\nFountain Inn, died yesterday in a\nnursing home at Hendersonville,\nN. C.\nThe bald headed paragrapher,\nhumorist and columnist long had\nbeen ill.\nThe former tramp printer\u2019s works\nwere widely syndicated and through\nhis writings he became known to\nfolks in every part of the United\nStates.\nAfter settling here, becoming pub\nlisher of the Fountain Inn Tribune\nand becoming prosperous through\nhis writings, Mr. Quillen put his\nadopted home town on the map.\nErected Statne of' Eve.\nHe erected a statue to Eve in\nhis yard\u2014an act widely heralded\nin the press. Visitors flocked here\nto view an eccentric, but found\nonly a mild-mannered, cultured\nman who never attended college.\n\u201cShe was a relative of mine on\nmy mother\u2019s side,\u201d he explained\nto those who inquired about the\nstatue.\nMany asked him why he \u201cburied\u201d\nhimself in a small town. So he\nwrote that he liked the neighborly,\nlife of a Southern small town, al\nthough every one knew when the\nmortgage was due on the house or\nwhether one paid cash for one\u2019s car,\nyet heaped little acts of kindness\nupon one in time of adversity or\nsorrow.\nSold Paper for $1.\nHe once broke into National\nprint by selling his newspaper for\n$1 because he was too busy to oper\nate it. But he soon grew hungry\nfor the odor of printer's ink and\nbought it back.\nThe Tribune once printed his\nobituary \u201cintended to help things\nalong for \\hose who survive.\u201d\n\u201cThink how thankful a desk man\nmust feel when told to prepare half\na column about a deceased brother\nof the press and discovers a copy\nalready written by the late lamented,\nhimself,\u201d he quipped.\nThe article said that Mr. Quillen\nwas \u201ca writer of paragraphs and\nshort editorials. He always hoped to\nwrite something of permanent value,\nbut the business of making a living\ntook all of his time and he never\ngot around to it.\u201d\nThe self-written obituary con\ncluded:\n\u201cAs neighbors and friends were\nreturning from the cemetery, Mr.\nT. 'H. McGee joined the widow to\nexpress his sympathy. \u2018It is a great\nloss,\u2019 he murmured. \u2018Yes,\u2019 she agreed\nabsently, \u2018but it is fully covered by\ninsurance.\u2019\nFilm Writer Found Hanged;\nBelieved Acting Out Part\nBy th* Associated Press\nNEWPORT BEACH, Calif., Dee.\n10.\u2014Clad in a woman\u2019s blue-and\nwhite sunsuit, a girdle and red shoes,\nthe body of Wilfred Pettitt, 38, a\nscreen writer, was found hanged;\naboard his yacht yesterday.\nPolice Chief R. R, Hodgkinson said\nit was not determined whether death\nwas a suicide or accident.\nOfficers considered the theory that\nMr. Pettitt may have been enacting\na scene from one of his dramas and\naccidentally choked in a makeshift\nnoose cut of ship\u2019s rope and cord.\nHis widow, Betty, said he some\ntimes worked out his roles with\ngreat realism.\nMr. Pettitt\u2019s body was hanvine\nfrom a bronze plate hook attached\nto a cabin rafter, Detective R. R.\nBurdsall reported. He'Said his In\nvestigation ruled foul play. A Aan\nuscript lay on the floor nearby.\nMrs. Pettitt said the writer had\ngone to .the yacht from his South\nPasadena home yesterday to work\non a new novel.\nMr. Pettitt, born in Liverpool, Eng\nland, had been a contract writer at\nColumbia Studio since 1942. He had\nwritten several published plays and\npoems in addition to such film scripts\nas \u201cThe Swordsman,\u201d \u201cThe Walls\nI Came Tumbling Down,\u201d \"The Bandit\nof Sherwood Forest,\u201d \u201cA Thousand\nand One Nights,\u201d and several of the\nWhistler series.\n\nSailing vessels are classed accord\ning to thp particular combination\nof spars, sail and cordage, and me\nwords \u201ccutter,\" \u201cbrig\u201d or \u201cship\u201d\nare really abbreviations for \u201ccutter\nrigged,\u201d \u201cbrig-rigged\u201d and \u201cship-.\nrigged.\u201d\nHere\u2019s How Our\nScientific\nPROFESSIONAL\nTREATMENTS\nft. W. FARRELL, Trichologist\nCan Help GRO W\nTHICKER HAIR\nFREE Examination Private Office Reasonable Rates\nTreatments taken in time\nsave money save hair!\nIt's unfortunate but true\nthat MOST BALD PEOPLE\ncould have saved their hair,\nand their looks, had they\nacted in time. A free, com\nprehensive hair and scalp\nexamination by one of Hair\nExperts' hair specialists will\ngive you a true picture of the\nactual condition of your\nscalp and its hair-growing\nability.\n\nHeaded for Baldnessf\nTake time out now and examine\nyour hair condition. If there is\nexcessive hair in your combings;\nif your scalp is itchy; if there is'\nunusual dryness or oiliness; if\nthere is heavy, clinging dandruff;\nif there are short weak hairs at\nyour frontal hairline then\nthere is some condition attacking\nyour normal hair growth. Delay\nmay be deadly. If an abnormal\nhair condition is allowed to flour\nish, fatal follicle shrinkage may\nresult and no treatments of\nany kind will be able to restore\nyour scalp to hair-growing ac\ntivity.\nHair Experts use the most mod\nern trichological methods in the\nnation to combat and replace hair\nloss. Ultra-violet lamp therapy,\nexclusive formulae created in Hair\nExperts' own laboratories, intensive\nprofessional stimulation, and mas\nsage are all scientifically timed and\ncombined to normalize ond return\nthe scalp to healthy, vigorous, virile\ngrowth. Treatments are pleasant\nand relaxing, are administered in\nprivate.\nHow Long Before\nPositive Resultsf\nFor most scalp-disorder cases that\nwe handle, it usually takes about\n4 or 5 weeks of concentrated\ntreatments to revitalize the scalp\n\u2014correct local disorders, purge\nout infectious germs, clear clog\nged hair passages; overcome com\nplex dandruff, normalize excessive\ndryness or oiliness and energize\nthe scalp to support and maintain\nthe growth of normal hair.\nIt will pay you to get a scolp\ncheck-up TODAY! There is no\ncharge or obligation for a free\ncomprehensive hair and scalp ex\namination at Hair Experts. Hope\nless cases are never accepted.\nEvening hours for your convenience.\n\u2022\u2014Modern, Science-Based Treatments\nNo Odorous Chomicalt or C rooty Ointments Utod\nAIR EXPERTS,,,\nOFFICES FROM COAST TO COAST\nOpen Doily 9 o.m. to 7 p.m.\u2014Saturday, 9 a.m. to 3 p.m.\nSuite 1050, Shoreham Bldg., Corner 15th and H Sts. N.W.\nPhone NAtional 6081\nU. S. Plans to Send\nMarines to Shanghai\nIf Emergency Occurs\n\u2022y th\u00bb A\u00bbeclat*d fr*it\nSHANGHAI, Dec. .10.\u2014United\nStates Marines will be moved into\nShanghai in an emergency to pro\ntect American lives, Vice Admiral\nOscar C. Badger announced today.\nThe commander of the United\nStates Fleet in the Western Pacific\ntold a press conference that \u201cwithin\nthe limits of reasonable feasibility\nthey would also protect America\u2019s\nprimary interests.\u201d\n(He did not elaborate on \u201cpri\nmary interests,\u201d but presumably\nhe meant they also would protect\nAmerican property.)\nMarines Not to Interfere.\nAdmiral Badger said any Marine\nlanding in Shanghai would be in no\nway \u201cintervention in Chinese do\nmestic affairs or in the civil war.\u201d\nMarines would be moved in to aid\nin the evacuation and definitely\nwould not come as a substitute for\nrecognized agencies of law and or\nder, he added.\nAdmiral, Badger also reported a\nNavy transport may put into Shang\nhai soon with a small group of Ma\nrines aboard \u201cwho would remain\nafloat.\u201d\nHe said he did not intend to put\nthem in shore billets, but they might\nbe given liberty ashore.\nThe admiral emphasized that any\nMarines would not be left in Shang\nhai beyond a period of emergency.\nMay Guard Power Plant,\nThe admiral conceded that the\nMarines also might be used to pro\ntect the Shanghai power plant\u2014a\nsubject of much speculation here.\nAsked what the Marines would do\nif retreating government troops\nmight try to blow up the plant as\na scorched earth measure, Admiral\nBadger replied, \"I think such a\nthing could be avoided by con\nversation rather than gunfire.\u201d\nIn the event of disorders, Ameri\ncan nationals in Shanghai will be\ntaken aboard Navy ships in the\nharbor. Some of these ships would\nremain here to accommodate Amer\nicans who would want to return to\nShanghai when order was restored.\nRobert Douglas, bom in Scone,\nScotland, was a student of fruit\nchemistry and in 1912 was able to!\nextract and prepare commercially1\nthe fruit ingredient pectin, which\nmakes fruit juices jell.\nCapital Goods Economcis\nTo Be Subject of Session\nThe 4th national conference in\ncapital goods economics will be held\nby the Machinery and Allied Pro\nducts Institute today and Saturday\nat the Mayflower Hotel. More than\n200 top officers of large capital goods\nindustries are expected to attend.\nCorwin Edwards, chief economist,\n(^vision of industrial economics Fed\neral Trade Commission, was sched\nuled to speak at today\u2019s session on\nthe \u201cBasing Point and Delivered\nPrice Controversy.\u201d The \"Business\nOutlook for 1949\u201d was to be dis\ncussed at a luncheon at 2:30 p.m. by\nDonald Woodward, vice president of\nthe Mutual Life Insurance Co. of\nNew York. The afternoon session\ntomorrow was to take up \"Work of\nthe Anglo-American Council on\nProductivity.\u201d\nPROMPT. ALMOST AMAZING RELIEF\nSKIN BLEMISHES\nwhen externally caused, try Cuticura\u2014prefer\nred by many doctors, nurses and certain hospi\ntals! Relieves pimples, rash, blemishes; softens\nblackheads for easy removal. Buy today!\nCUTICURA OnffMENT\nLifer, Right Arm Gone, Paints\nPatton's Portrait With Left\n\u2022y th* Associated Press\nMcALESTER, Okla., Dec. 10.\u2014It\ntook eight long years of patient\npractice, but William Samet is con\nvinced he can paint just as skill\nfully with his left hand.\nFolks who have seen his life-size\noil of Gen. George S. Patton are\ninclined to agree.\nThe artist\u2019s right arm\u2014shattered\nin a gun fight- after he robbed an\nOklahoma City theater in 1940\u2014is\ngone now. He is serving a life term\nin the Oklahoma State Penitentiary.\nIn 1939, one of Samet\u2019s paintings\nwon a $25 prize in an exhibition at\nthe Museum of Modern Art in New\nYork. His biographical sketch ap\npears in Sidney Janis\u2019 book, \u201cThey\nTaught Themselves,\u201d along with\nthose of three other self-taught\nartists.\nPING-PONG TABLES\nTOPS\u2014BOTTOMS\nHESLOP\nLUMBER MILLWORK CO.\n784 EYE ST. 8.W. NA. 8448\nHis first left-handed portrait,\n\u201cBlood and Guts,\u201d was finished alter\na week of full-time work. Saraet\nfeels it is as good as any he has\never done.\n\u201cf\u2019d like to keep it myself,\u201d he\nsaid, \u201cbut it\u2019s a little large for my\ncell.\"\nThe painting will be offered tot\nsale through the prison store.\nWork on Dual Highway\nTo York, Pa., Started\n\u25a0y tho Associated Prsu\nTTMONIUM, Md., Dec. 10.\u2014Work\nstarted yesterday on the first sec\ntions of a projected dual highway\nfrom Baltimore to York, Pa.\nThe first segment is a 4-mils\nstretch near here. A $753,193 con\ntract for grading and draining It\nwas awarded this week. William P.\nChilds, chief engineer, said bids\nwould be asked on other sections as\nsoon as surveys have b*en completed\nand the specifications drawn up.\ntflVTS\nFOR THE HOME!\nBICYCLE. Sturdy all\nmetal frame. Big balloon\ntires. Has kick stand.\n$4295\nPmy $1.00 a V\"**k!\nDOLL CARRIAGE. Has\na 3-bow hood and stitched\nleatherette body.\nChart\u2022 it!\n.11\nMETAL WAGON. Bright\nred enamel finish. Long\nhandle. Rubber tires.\nCharge it!\nTRICYCLE. All metal.\nRubber tires. Comfortable\neasy seat. Easy to pedal.\n$0.39\nROLLER SKATES. Easy\nrolling, ball beaiing\nwheels. Padded ankle\nstraps.\n$J.95\nCharge it!\nDESK AND CHAIR SET.\nSlanting desk top. Sturdy\nchair. Gay maple finish.\n$0.95\n3-PIECE MAHOGANY BEDROOM\n^Elegant 18th Century style! Lus\ntrous mahogany finish. You get bed,\nchest and vanity or dresser.\nPay Only $1.7S a Week!\nf TAPESTRY\nSECTIONAL SOFA\n$fl9.95\nArrongf if anyway you like\nWakes conventional sofa or smart\ngroup.\nPay f,.SO Weekly,\nSOFA BED\n$46i45\nWalnut-arm modern sofa bed in bright\ntapestry. Opens to big double bed.\nHas big bedding comportment.\n$3.00 Down\nCEDAR CHESTS\n*38\u2019M\nModern waterfall chest in rich grained\nwalnut veneer. Lined in genuine \u2022moth\nproof cedar. Has troy that lifts with lid.\nPay 75c a week\nCOMBINATION\nTABLE RADIO\nRich, surging, life-like\ntons. Ploys 12 records\ncontinuously.\nPay $1.25 a Weak!\n18th\nCENTURY\nMAHOGANY\nSECRETARY\nBeautiful period style\nwith 13-pane glass\ndoors and swing-open'\ndesk top.\nS67T5\nPay $1.25\na Wank!\nTWIN WAFFLE IRON\n*10\u201c\nServes 'em up 2 at a time.. .piping\nhot and crispy brown.\nChargt it!\nAUTOMATIC\nTOASTER\n$2| 50\nI Famous GE quality.\nChrome plated. Pops\nup toast when done.\nCharta it l\nLOUNGE\nCHAIR\n%MM\nFigured tapestry cover, t'\nholstered arm. Comfortob'\nspring-filled teat.\n$3.00 Down/\nIk. ..A.\nSIL HEATER\n*79\u201c\nBig modern heater! Heats\n2 to 3 rooms. Thrifty on\nfuel. Rich finish.\n$5.00 Down!\ni'v.\nCocktail Table\nAttractive pie-crust trim.\nShimmering glass top. Wol\ni nut finish.\n$14.50\nCharg* Ht\nELECTRIC WASHER\n\ntig tub takes on 8-lb.\nload turns out the\nfreshest, whitest wash\nyou've ever seen.\nPay $1.2S a Waak!","height":"32052","width":"22252"}}
